{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YZmGu7pKDYasqZMnQBaQVj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here's the summary:\n\n---\n\n## Results\n\n### Step 1 — Diagnosis\nNo configuration bugs were found preventing jobs from running. The cluster (master + worker) came up cleanly, and all three job YAMLs were correctly configured to run `--master local[2]` (self-contained, no cluster submission required).\n\n### Step 2 — Baseline (no optimization)\n- **Strategy:** Skewed shuffle join — `product_id` repartition sends 50% of orders to 5 hot-product partitions\n- **Elapsed: 27.8s**\n- The uneven partition sizes create stragglers (one task holds up the whole stage)\n\n### Step 3 — Broadcast Join Optimization\n- **Strategy:** Broadcasts the small `products` table (100 rows) to every executor, eliminating the shuffle entirely\n- **Elapsed: 14.8s** — **47% faster** than baseline\n- `spark.sql.autoBroadcastJoinThreshold=10MB` ensures the products table is broadcast\n\n### Step 4 — AQE (Adaptive Query Execution) Optimization\n- **Strategy:** Spark detects skewed partitions at runtime and auto-splits them\n- **Elapsed: 18.79s** — **33% faster** than baseline\n- Configured with `skewJoin.enabled=true` and a very low threshold to force detection\n\n### Performance Comparison\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed | Improvement |\n|---|---|---|\n| Baseline (no optimization) | 27.8s | — |\n| **Broadcast join** | **14.8s** | **47% faster** |\n| AQE skew join | 18.79s | 33% faster |\n\n**Winner: Broadcast join** — for a small dimension table like `products` (100 rows), eliminating the shuffle entirely outperforms AQE's runtime partition splitting. AQE is more useful when the dimension table is too large to broadcast."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":436,"cache_read_input_tokens":41690,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_